Second Derivative Using Central Difference in Excel
Overview
This project demonstrates the implementation of the **Central Difference O(h²)** method using **Microsoft Excel** to approximate the second derivative of a mathematical function.
The analysis is performed using two different step sizes (*h*) to investigate how the interval size influences the accuracy of the numerical approximation. The numerical results are compared with the analytical solution through relative error analysis.

Objectives
- Implement the Central Difference O(h²) method in Microsoft Excel.
- Approximate the second derivative of a mathematical function.
- Evaluate the influence of different step sizes on approximation accuracy.
- Compare numerical results with the analytical derivative.
- Visualize the function using charts.

Methods
The following numerical differentiation method is implemented:
- Central Difference O(h²)

The analysis is carried out using two different step sizes:
-h = 0.10
-h = 0.01

Results
| Step Size | Approximation | Relative Error |
|-----------|--------------:|---------------:|
| h = 0.10 | 36.6419535041 | 0.132% |
| h = 0.01 | **36.5940197930** | **0.0013%** |
The comparison shows that reducing the step size significantly improves the approximation accuracy. The **Central Difference O(h²)** method achieves an approximation very close to the analytical derivative when a smaller interval is used.

